# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: streamgraph
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] An **area chart** or **area graph** displays graphically quantitative data.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] The area between axis and line are commonly emphasized with colors, textures and hatchings.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] Commonly one compares two or more quantities with an area chart.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] William Playfair is usually credited with inventing the area charts as well as the line, bar, and pie charts.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] Area charts are used to represent cumulated totals using numbers or percentages (stacked area charts in this case) over time.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] Use the area chart for showing trends over time among related attributes.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] The area chart is like the plot chart except that the area below the plotted line is filled in with color to indicate volume.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] When multiple attributes are included, the first attribute is plotted as a line with color fill followed by the second attribute, and so on.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] Area charts which use vertical and horizontal lines to connect the data points in a series forming a step-like progression are called *step-area charts*.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] Area charts in which data points are connected by smooth curves instead of straight lines are called *spline-area charts*.
[src:streamgraph/area-chart] Stacked area charts in which the area is displaced around the central axis are called *streamgraphs*.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] A **fan chart** is made of a group of dispersion fan diagrams, which may be positioned according to two categorising dimensions.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] A *dispersion fan diagram* is a circular diagram which reports the same information about a dispersion as a box plot: namely median, quartiles, and two extreme values.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] 4. two *feathers* which indicate the extreme values.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The scale on the circular line begins at the left with the starting value (e. g. with zero).
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The following values are applicated clockwise.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The white tail of diameter indicates the median.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The dark fan indicates the dispersion of the middle half of the observed values; thus it encompasses the values from the first to the third quartile.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The white feathers indicate the dispersion of the middle 90% of the observed values.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The length of the white part of the diameter corresponds with the number of observations.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] A fan chart gives a quick summary of observed values which depend from two variables.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] This is possible thanks of a dense representation and a constant size which does not depend on the size of the single dispersion fan diagrams.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] An essential advantage compared to a sequence of box plots is the possibility to compare dispersion fan diagrams not only within one direction but within two directions (horizontally and vertically).
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The following example presents data from the data set *MathAchieve* which is part of the R package *nlme* of José Pinheiro et al.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] It contains mathematics achievement scores of 7185 students.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The students are categorised according to sex and membership of a minority ethnic group.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The graphics show the mathematics achievement scores in dependency on the socio-economic status of the students (x axis) and on the average socio-economic status of all students at the same school (y axis).
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The four graphic panels differentiate the students according to sex and membership of a minority ethnic group.
[src:streamgraph/fan-chart-statistics] The fan charts reveals clearly how the median value is partially following a big main tendency while the values of the single subgroups (with the cells) scatter largely what could lead to doubts about a possible correlation.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:streamgraph/stacked-bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] A **streamgraph**, or **stream graph**, is a type of stacked area graph which is displaced around a central axis, resulting in a flowing, organic shape.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Unlike a traditional stacked area graph in which the layers are stacked on top of an axis, in a streamgraph the layers are positioned to minimize their "wiggle".
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] More formally, the layers are displaced to minimize the sum of the squared slopes of each layer, weighted by the area of the layer.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Streamgraphs display data with only positive values, and are not able to represent both negative and positive values.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Streamgraphs and their use were popularized by Amanda Cox in a February 2008 *New York Times* article on movie box office revenues.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Cox got the idea from then-undergraduate Lee Byron, who had used a similar method for visualizing his music listening history.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] A related graph, sometimes conflated with streamgraphs, is the ThemeRiver, in which the "silhouette" of the graph is symmetrically arranged around the central axis.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Streamgraphs were found to be more readable than basic stacked area graphs or ThemeRivers for value comparison tasks.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Streamgraphs are officially supported by Matplotlib and D3.js.
[src:streamgraph/streamgraph] Marco Di Bartolomeo and Yifan Hu (2016) propose several improvements to streamgraphs, such as using 1-norm minimization instead of 2-norm minimization.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:streamgraph/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:streamgraph/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
